<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-624-271  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 624 271.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Nov 20 1990 v4 n40 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Macweek 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft technology to tie Mac to Windows. (includes relatedarticle on Windows jargon)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wylie, Margie.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Microsoft Inc is announcing that the new application programminginterfaces (API) the company is developing will allow AppleMacintosh developers to create universal applications that can usethe same files as those on IBM microcomputers and compatibles.andO;The new technology will translate to operating system extensionsto both Macintosh and Windows environments.andP;  Microsoft contendsthat some of the extensions will be comparable to theInterapplication Communications facilities of Macintosh's System7.0.andP;  However, they will function as an API that rides on top ofSystem 7.0.andP;  Microsoft feels that all vendors will want to use thenew technologies but other analysts disagree, feeling that onlyvendors who have real cross-platform applications will embrace thenew technology.andP;  Since neither System 7.0 or Microsoft'sextensions are on the market yet, it is impossible to know howboth will work.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Products)Apple Computer Inc. (Products).andO;Ticker:    AAPL; MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows (Graphical user interface) (Usage)Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (Computer programs)System 7.0 (Operating system) (Product enhancement).andO;Topic:     Operating SystemsApplications Programming InterfaceSoftware DesignProgram Development TechniquesGraphical User InterfaceEnhancements.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microsoft technology to tie Mac to WindowsandM;Las Vegas -- What's good for Windows users is good for Mac users.andP;  At leastthat seemed to be Microsoft Corp.'s message at Comdex/Fall '90 last week whenthe company announced it also would embrace the Mac with its new Windowstechnologies.andM;Wrapped in a haze of terms such as &quot;linking&quot; and &quot;embedding&quot; (see relatedstory, Page 8), the technologies will take on flesh as operating systemextensions to both the Windows and Macintosh environments, the company said.andM;According to Mike Maples, Microsoft vice president of applications, some ofthe extensions will be similar to the Interapplication Communicationsfacilities of System 7.0 but will function as an application programminginterface (API) that rides on top of System 7.0.andM;But why would Macintosh application developers use Microsoft's facilitiesrather than those built into System 7.0?andM;Two reasons, said Maples: consistency across platforms and because Microsoftdoes it better.andM;Using Microsoft's APIs, for example, developers will be able to create&quot;universal&quot; applications that can use the same files as those on IBM PCs andcompatibles as well as write links with PC applications.andP;  &quot;We think thatevery vendor will want to use these technologies,&quot; Maples said.andM;Stewart Alsop, publisher of the P.C.andP;  Letter in Redwood City, Calif.,andO;disagreed.andP;  &quot;Those vendors who have a real cross-platform application willconform.andP;  But vendors with Mac-only applications couldn't care less,&quot; hesaid.andM;The new Windows technologies also will improve on System 7.0, Maples said.andM;&quot;Our complementary set of abilities adds, on top of AppleEvents and Publishand Subscribe, the ability to do hot links and embedding that doesn't existin the present system software,&quot; he said.andM;Microsoft's hot links will automatically update information in a linkeddocument every time it is changed in the parent document, Maples said.andO;System 7.0's linking facilities are updated only when the new information issaved, he said.andM;Others said they see little difference between the two approaches.andM;&quot;Apple and Microsoft are both solving the same problems.andP;  Only Apple -- intypical Apple fashion -- is doing it in a way that users will understand.andO;And Microsoft -- in typical Microsoft fashion -- is doing it in a way thatdevelopers and programmers will understand,&quot; Alsop said.andM;Still, it's impossible to know how either System 7.0 or Microsoft'sextensions will work until they are both on the market, according to Alsop.andO;Until then, users and developers can only speculate.andP;  &quot;The problem right nowis that none of this stuff is implemented,&quot; he said.andM;Microsoft said it hopes to release the API that will let vendors invoke thesetechnologies by year-end.andP;  It would not, however, reveal which or how manyMacintosh developers have signed up to base their applications on its scheme.andO;Maples claimed that Microsoft is working closely with Apple and Claris, butdeclined to provide details.andM;Apple's System 7.0, after many delays, is now set to ship in the secondquarter of 1991.andO;</TEXT></DOC>